Creating images with R

With a little bit of magick

Wenyu Yu

2023-03-07

My meme

I have been looking for a series of three funny memes for hours to concatenate them together; there is no common topic or category that can be attributed to the three memes.

library(magick)

# first meme
formula <- image_read("./pic/formula.jpg") %>% image_scale(600)

# first meme comment
formula_text <- image_blank(width = 600, 
                          height = 550, 
                          color = "#5865f2") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Knowledge reveals truth",
                 color = "#000000",
                 size = 40,
                 font = "impact",
                 gravity = "center")

# second meme
programming <- image_read("./pic/programming.jpg") %>% image_scale(600)

# second meme comment
programming_text <- image_blank(width = 600, 
                          height = 550, 
                          color = "#5865f2") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Is HTML a coding language?",
                 color = "#000000",
                 size = 40,
                 font = "Impact",
                 gravity = "center")

# third meme
revolution <- image_read("./pic/revolution.jpg") %>% image_scale(600)

#third meme comment
revolution_text <- image_blank(width = 600, 
                               height = 300, 
                               color = "#5865f2") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Human revolution",
                 color = "#000000",
                 size = 40,
                 font = "Impact",
                 gravity = "center")

# concatenate pictures of memes with comments of memes
top_row <- image_append(c(formula, formula_text))
middle_row <- image_append(c(programming, programming_text))
bottom_row <- image_append(c(revolution, revolution_text))

# create the whole series of memes
meme <- (c(top_row, middle_row, bottom_row) %>%
    image_append(stack = TRUE) %>%
    image_scale(700))

# write the output as a jpeg file
image_write(meme, "my_meme.jpg")

My animation gif

Since the animation gif requires 4 frames, I started looking for topics with a period of four occurrences and seasons come naturally to my mind.

library(magick)

# creating a vector for the four seasons

season = c("Summer", "Autumn", "Winter", "Spring")

# creating each frame of the four seasons, with text from the season vector

frame1 <- image_read("./pic/summer.png") %>%
  image_scale(350) %>%
  image_annotate(text = season[1], size = 40, gravity = "center")

frame2 <- image_read("./pic/autumn.png") %>%
  image_scale(350) %>%
  image_annotate(text = season[2], size = 40, gravity = "center")

frame3 <- image_read("./pic/winter.png") %>%
  image_scale(350) %>%
  image_annotate(text = season[3], size = 40, gravity = "center")

frame4 <- image_read("./pic/spring.png") %>%
  image_scale(350) %>%
  image_annotate(text = season[4], size = 40, gravity = "center")

# putting the frames in order using a vector
frames <- c(frame1, frame2, frame3, frame4)
  
# creating an animation
animation <- (image_morph(frames) %>%
  image_animate(fps=4) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "As time flows!", size = 50, gravity = "north"))

# write the output as a gif file
image_write(animation, "my_animation.gif")
